I know this is not a direct answer but it is a much better solution. You should compact all of your data into a byte array with a set format. Serialization takes a long time and if you know the data you&#39;re sending you don&#39;t need to use such an unspecific algorithm which takes a long time in comparison to just doing the serialization yourself.
I don&#39;t actually know what data you&#39;re sending in the Animal class but lets say you send the species (a string variable), the age and a boolean representing whether the animal is fully-grown or not.

    class Animal {
        /* Fields and Constructors here */

        public static byte[] toByteArray(Animal a) {
            byte[] arr = new byte[a.name.length() + 4 /*(length of array)*/ + 4 /*(the age)*/ + 1 /*(fully-grown)*/];

            arr[0] = a.name.length() &gt;&gt; 24 &amp; 0xff;
            arr[1] = a.name.length() &gt;&gt; 16 &amp; 0xff;
            arr[2] = a.name.length() &gt;&gt; 8 &amp; 0xff;
            arr[3] = a.name.length() &amp; 0xff;

            for (int i = 0; i &lt; a.name.length(); i++) {
                arr[i + 4] = a.name.charAt(i);
            }

            arr[a.name.length() + 4] = a.age &gt;&gt; 24 &amp; 0xff;
            arr[a.name.length() + 5] = a.age &gt;&gt; 16 &amp; 0xff;
            arr[a.name.length() + 6] = a.age &gt;&gt; 8 &amp; 0xff;
            arr[a.name.length() + 7] = a.age &amp; 0xff;

            arr[a.name.length() + 8] = a.grown? 0x1 : 0x0;
        }
    }

